│ [968, 972, "llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp"], [987, 1013,              │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the  │
│ Issue:\nThe globalopt pass transforms a pattern where a global pointer @g is  │
│ initialized once with the result of malloc and later compared to null. During │
│ OptimizeGlobalAddressOfAllocation it introduces an auxiliary global           │
│ `<name>.init` (InitBool) meant to track whether initialization happened. For  │
│ each store to the original global it creates a store of a boolean (true if    │
│ non-null) to InitBool; for each load+icmp against null it replaces the        │
│ comparison with logic using the boolean. However, when the original           │
│ loads/stores are atomic (as in the reproducer: seq_cst atomic load/store of a │
│ pointer), the transformation copies the atomic ordering onto new atomic       │
│ load/store instructions of type i1. LLVM IR forbids atomic memory operations  │
│ whose operand size is not a whole number of bytes (LangRef: atomic objects    │
│ must be at least one byte and power-of-two sized). An i1 atomic load/store is │
│ invalid, and the verifier rightly rejects the IR, causing the abort.\n\n2.    │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe crash happens after running globalopt and then the  │
│ verifier. The log shows: \"atomic memory access' size must be byte-sized\"    │
│ followed by the invalid instructions:\n  store atomic i1 true, ptr @g.init    │
│ seq_cst\n  %g.init.val = load atomic i1, ptr @g.init seq_cst\nThese           │
│ instructions are exactly those emitted in OptimizeGlobalAddressOfAllocation   │
│ at lines 968-972 (store) and 987-991 (load). No other transformations occur   │
│ before verification; thus the first transformation point introducing invalid  │
│ IR is in globalopt itself.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nCode creating          │
│ InitBool:\n  GlobalVariable *InitBool = new                                   │
│ GlobalVariable(Type::getInt1Ty(...)\nThen store:\n  new StoreInst(i1, ...,    │
│ SI->getOrdering(), ...)\nAnd load:\n  new LoadInst(i1, ...,                   │
│ LI->getOrdering(), ...)\nIt unconditionally preserves the original atomic     │
│ ordering (seq_cst here). This yields atomic ops on i1. For correctness we     │
│ must either: (a) drop atomic semantics (unsafe — changes memory model), (b)   │
│ keep atomic semantics but change InitBool to have a byte-sized type, or (c)   │
│ widen the operations (e.g., use i8) and adjust the replacement logic for      │
│ comparisons. Dropping atomic breaks happens-before guarantees of original     │
│ program. Thus the correct fix is to use an i8 sentinel (byte-sized) for       │
│ atomic operations while still producing an i1 result for the predicate in a   │
│ defined way. Because existing replacement logic relies on bitwise not of an   │
│ i1 (BinaryOperator::CreateNot) to model (ptr == null) by !init, switching to  │
