│ load/store instructions of type i1. LLVM IR forbids atomic memory operations  │
│ whose operand size is not a whole number of bytes (LangRef: atomic objects    │
│ must be at least one byte and power-of-two sized). An i1 atomic load/store is │
│ invalid, and the verifier rightly rejects the IR, causing the abort.          │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The crash happens after running globalopt and then the verifier. The log      │
│ shows: "atomic memory access' size must be byte-sized" followed by the        │
│ invalid instructions:                                                         │
│   store atomic i1 true, ptr @g.init seq_cst                                   │
│   %g.init.val = load atomic i1, ptr @g.init seq_cst                           │
│ These instructions are exactly those emitted in                               │
│ OptimizeGlobalAddressOfAllocation at lines 968-972 (store) and 987-991        │
│ (load). No other transformations occur before verification; thus the first    │
│ transformation point introducing invalid IR is in globalopt itself.           │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ Code creating InitBool:                                                       │
│   GlobalVariable *InitBool = new GlobalVariable(Type::getInt1Ty(...)          │
│ Then store:                                                                   │
│   new StoreInst(i1, ..., SI->getOrdering(), ...)                              │
│ And load:                                                                     │
│   new LoadInst(i1, ..., LI->getOrdering(), ...)                               │
│ It unconditionally preserves the original atomic ordering (seq_cst here).     │
│ This yields atomic ops on i1. For correctness we must either: (a) drop atomic │
│ semantics (unsafe — changes memory model), (b) keep atomic semantics but      │
│ change InitBool to have a byte-sized type, or (c) widen the operations (e.g., │
│ use i8) and adjust the replacement logic for comparisons. Dropping atomic     │
│ breaks happens-before guarantees of original program. Thus the correct fix is │
│ to use an i8 sentinel (byte-sized) for atomic operations while still          │
│ producing an i1 result for the predicate in a defined way. Because existing   │
│ replacement logic relies on bitwise not of an i1 (BinaryOperator::CreateNot)  │
│ to model (ptr == null) by !init, switching to i8 requires altering that       │
│ logic: we should compare the loaded i8 against 0 (icmp eq/ne) instead of      │
│ bitwise not, to preserve semantics.                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Points(s):                                                   │
│ Edit 1 (lines 955-958): Change the InitBool global type from i1 to i8         │
│ (Type::getInt8Ty). Keep initializer 0. This ensures subsequent atomic         │
│ operations are valid. Adjust ConstantInt::getFalse to                         │
│ ConstantInt::get(Type::getInt8Ty, 0).                                         │
│ Edit 2 (lines 968-972): Replace ConstantInt::getBool with creation of an i8   │
│ 0/1 constant (APInt(8, Value)). Store remains atomic with original ordering.  │
│ Edit 3 (lines 987-1013): Replace load of i1 with load of i8, remove           │
