  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe globalopt pass transforms a
pattern where a global pointer @g is initialized once with the result of malloc
and later compared to null. During OptimizeGlobalAddressOfAllocation it
introduces an auxiliary global `<name>.init` (InitBool) meant to track whether
initialization happened. For each store to the original global it creates a store
of a boolean (true if non-null) to InitBool; for each load+icmp against null it
replaces the comparison with logic using the boolean. However, when the original
loads/stores are atomic (as in the reproducer: seq_cst atomic load/store of a
pointer), the transformation copies the atomic ordering onto new atomic
load/store instructions of type i1. LLVM IR forbids atomic memory operations
whose operand size is not a whole number of bytes (LangRef: atomic objects must
be at least one byte and power-of-two sized). An i1 atomic load/store is invalid,
and the verifier rightly rejects the IR, causing the abort.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's
Log:\nThe crash happens after running globalopt and then the verifier. The log
shows: \"atomic memory access' size must be byte-sized\" followed by the invalid
instructions:\n  store atomic i1 true, ptr @g.init seq_cst\n  %g.init.val = load
atomic i1, ptr @g.init seq_cst\nThese instructions are exactly those emitted in
OptimizeGlobalAddressOfAllocation at lines 968-972 (store) and 987-991 (load). No
other transformations occur before verification; thus the first transformation
point introducing invalid IR is in globalopt itself.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nCode creating InitBool:\n  GlobalVariable *InitBool = new
GlobalVariable(Type::getInt1Ty(...)\nThen store:\n  new StoreInst(i1, ...,
SI->getOrdering(), ...)\nAnd load:\n  new LoadInst(i1, ..., LI->getOrdering(),
...)\nIt unconditionally preserves the original atomic ordering (seq_cst here).
This yields atomic ops on i1. For correctness we must either: (a) drop atomic
semantics (unsafe \u2014 changes memory model), (b) keep atomic semantics but
change InitBool to have a byte-sized type, or (c) widen the operations (e.g., use
i8) and adjust the replacement logic for comparisons. Dropping atomic breaks
happens-before guarantees of original program. Thus the correct fix is to use an
i8 sentinel (byte-sized) for atomic operations while still producing an i1 result
for the predicate in a defined way. Because existing replacement logic relies on
bitwise not of an i1 (BinaryOperator::CreateNot) to model (ptr == null) by !init,
switching to i8 requires altering that logic: we should compare the loaded i8
against 0 (icmp eq/ne) instead of bitwise not, to preserve semantics.\n\n4.
Proposed Edit Points(s):\nEdit 1 (lines 955-958): Change the InitBool global type
from i1 to i8 (Type::getInt8Ty). Keep initializer 0. This ensures subsequent
atomic operations are valid. Adjust ConstantInt::getFalse to
ConstantInt::get(Type::getInt8Ty, 0).\nEdit 2 (lines 968-972): Replace
ConstantInt::getBool with creation of an i8 0/1 constant (APInt(8, Value)). Store
remains atomic with original ordering.\nEdit 3 (lines 987-1013): Replace load of
i1 with load of i8, remove BinaryOperator::CreateNot. Introduce IRBuilder at ICI
location to build icmp eq/ne against constant 0 producing i1 results. For EQ and
ULE predicates: result is (load == 0). For NE and UGT: result is (load != 0). For
ULT/UGE remain constant false/true. Remove use of CreateNot which assumes i1.
Preserve debug locations and ordering. Maintain InitBoolUsed flag.\nThese edits
retain atomic seq_cst semantics while generating verifier-legal IR and equivalent
logical behavior.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash stems from generating atomic i1
loads/stores, which violate IR constraints. By widening the InitBool tracking
global to i8 and adjusting comparison rewriting logic to use icmp (eq/ne with
zero) instead of not, we produce valid atomic instructions, keep memory ordering
guarantees, and preserve semantic equivalence. The specified edits correct the IR
produced by globalopt, preventing verifier failure and abort.\n",
